centralized internet for those who want it, and vehemently agree that not e=
verybody will.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">We&#8217;d go even further than our oppone=
nts and say that <strong>a fully decentralized future is impossible</strong=
>. Some people will always prefer centralized services for everything, many=
 more will prefer fully decentralized services for some things and centrali=
zed ones for others.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">But this debate is not about central=
ization versus decentralization. It&#8217;s about <strong>choice</strong>.&=
nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>This debate is about whether or not web3, an inte=
rnet owned by the users and builders, orchestrated with tokens, is net good=
 or net bad for humanity, not just as it stands today in its earliest form,=
 but in the promise it holds.</strong> (<em>See what I did there?)</em></p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;">It&#8217;s about whether the world will be better if entrepreneurs=
